		<header>
			
			<h1>Debate on the future of the CAP intensifies</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>After the publication in September 2010 of a French-German common position on the CAP after 2013, on 15 October the Italian government released a declaration supporting the Franco-German position. France's Farm Minister Bruno Lemaire now claims that ‘around 20 EU governments’ supported the Franco-German proposals. However some member states governments are critical, with Polish Farm Minister Marek Sawicki arguing that ‘the Franco-German position is a very conservative one. It defends the interests of their farmers, but not of farmers from other member states.’ A key issue in this regard is the future distribution of direct aid payments across the EU. Mr Sawicki described the Franco-German initiative as ‘a rather unsuccessful attempt to exert pressure on other member states’, while the UK Agriculture Minister, Caroline Spelman, pointed out that the Lisbon Treaty is now more complex, and ‘even if you're two big states out of the 27, you can't dictate terms.’</p><p>Meanwhile, farmers’ organisations have reacted to the Commission communication on ‘The CAP towards 2020’, warning that ‘the plans do not enable EU farmers and their cooperatives to fulfil their economic role of producing food and services for 500 million consumers.’ Copa-Cogeca maintained that ‘whilst addressing some environmental concerns, the plans fail to address the economic problems of farmers.’ They also criticised the EC communication for lack of detail on the specific measures to be introduced to improve the functioning of the supply chain.</p><p>COPE-COGECA favours a continuation of direct aid payments, with no significant reshaping of pillar 1, and with pillar 2 being used to ‘deliver additionality, provide targeted services and agri-environment measures’.</p><p>Regarding the effects of the CAP on agriculture in developing countries, the French NGO umbrella body, Coordination SUD,<i> </i>has recently published an executive brief on ‘The CAP and developing countries’. This briefing note argues in favour of food sovereignty for developing countries, including allowing protection of their markets in order to prevent imports from the EU disrupting local agricultural production. The analysis points out that since direct aid payments can still allow EU exports to take place at prices below the actual costs of production, ‘dumping is thus still possible’. In this context the paper argues that developing countries should be allowed to retain a range of policy tools to respond to this new form of dumping, including the use of import bans (for example for potatoes and onions in Guinea), quantitative restrictions (e.g. for chicken in Cameroon), tariff increases (e.g. for milk in Kenya), variable tariffs and levies according to the domestic market conditions (e.g. beef in the EU), and the use of a value added tax (e.g. chicken in Cameroon).</p>
		
		
