				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Many of the criticisms of the recent EC communication relate to the lack of specific proposals. This is to be expected since the EC is seeking to build consensus amongst member states on the broad approach to be adopted. This implies that ACP governments should pay close attention to how, in specific sectors, they would like to see these emerging principles applied, so as to minimise the negative effects of this further round of CAP reform on ACP economies. This will require a detailed, sector-by-sector analysis of possible modalities for the implementation of these principles, the effects of specific changes on the use of current policy tools and their likely implications for the ACP. This needs to include an analysis of the possible knock-on effects of specific policy changes on other policy tools and other policy areas.</p><p>One issue of potential external importance is how direct farm payments will be structured. The Commission proposes the 'capping' of the payments to farms. Such changes could be important, since it is generally the larger farms that are most efficient, so the effect could be to restrain total European production, especially if another Commission proposal, to include a mandatory ‘green’ element to direct payments, is also agreed.</p><p>Of potential importance for ACP exporters are several references to the need to improve ‘the functioning of the food supply chain’. It is possible that any moves to limit the negotiating strength of the supermarkets could have spillover effects on ACP as well as European farmers.</p><p>The call of Coordination SUD for the protection of agricultural markets in developing countries needs to be seen in the context of the unresolved contentious issues in the EPA negotiations.</p>
		</div>
		
